"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142109","Treasury","false","2019-09-03","<p>In January 2018 the Charity Commission was allocated an additional £5m per year from the Government to help it respond to significant increases in demand on its core regulatory functions. Any future funding will be decided as part of the upcoming Spending Round.</p>","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Mr Simon Clarke",,"2019-09-03T08:03:00.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142109/answer","Biography information for Mr Simon Clarke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142109/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-07-25","Charity Commission: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to increase funding to the Charity Commission in order to investigate complaints against charities and build public trust in the charitable sector.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","282298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142110","Home Office","false","2019-09-06","<p>Asylum seekers are allowed to work in the UK if their claim has been outstanding for 12 months, through no fault of their own. Those permitted to work are restricted to jobs on the shortage occupation list published by the Home Office. The Home Office is currently reviewing this matter.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-09-06T13:31:43.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142110/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142110/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-25","Asylum: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to review the restrictions that prevent asylum seekers from working.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","282458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142111","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-09-09","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-09-09T16:24:17.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142111/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142111/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-07-25","Plastics: Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she has plans to review Government policy on tackling plastics pollution.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","282459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142119","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-03","<p>Local highways authorities are responsible for decisions on cycle lanes in their areas, including on whether or not these should be segregated from other road traffic. The Department is currently in the process of updating its guidance note to local authorities on Cycle Infrastructure Design, which includes advice on where and when different forms of segregation might be appropriate, and the updated guidance will be published in due course.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-09-03T16:40:02.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142119/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142119/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-25","Cycleways: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to support the construction of new cycle lanes that are separate from roads.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","282239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142120","Department for International Development","false","2019-09-03","<p>The UK remains extremely concerned by constraints on humanitarian access within Yemen. We regularly raise obstructions to humanitarian access and aid distributions with all parties at the highest levels and call for compliance with the UN Security Council Resolution 2451.</p><p> </p><p>The Foreign Secretary discussed the issue of humanitarian access across Yemen with his Government of Yemen counterparts earlier this year, and on 17 July UK officials raised the issue with the Government of Yemen’s Prime Minister Maeen Abdulmalik Saeed in Riyadh. I discussed it during my visit in the Gulf region last week. The UK will continue to press this issue with senior Yemeni counterparts.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-09-03T16:21:41.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142120/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142120/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-07-25","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans he has to meet his Yemeni counterpart to discuss how aid can reach people in need without being intercepted and captured by Houthi rebels.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","282299"
